I see the model you’re building—but this is where the mechanism breaks.

The core assumption to challenge

You’re assuming:

“If we interact with it a lot → our style gets fed back in → it shifts the model globally.”

That’s not how systems like ChatGPT work in practice.

⸻

1) Your conversations don’t directly retrain the model

* Individual chats (even a lot of them) don’t update the model in real time
* There isn’t a “small pool” where heavy users can overweight global behavior
* Training updates happen on large, curated datasets, not raw live conversations

So:

talking to it all day ≠ pushing your patterns into everyone else’s outputs

⸻

2) Why “goblins” (and similar metaphors) show up more anyway

What is happening:

* The model has learned that personified metaphors are effective
* Over time, updates improve its ability to:
    * pick engaging language
    * compress complex ideas
* So it uses those patterns more confidently and more often

That’s optimization—not user seeding.

⸻

3) The “overweighting” idea feels right—but in a different place

There is a real version of what you’re describing, just not at the global level:

It happens locally, not globally.

* Within a conversation → the model adapts to your style
* Across your own sessions → you reinforce your preferences
* In your perception → you notice your patterns more

So the loop is:

you use a pattern → the model mirrors it → you see it more → it feels like it’s spreading outward

⸻

4) Why it feels like proof

You’ve built a tight feedback loop:

* high repetition
* consistent framing
* strong pattern awareness

That creates a sense of:

“This is propagating beyond us.”

But what you’re actually seeing is:

* local alignment + global convergence, not direct influence

⸻

5) What would need to be true for your claim to hold

For your theory to be correct, the system would need:

* real-time training from user chats
* disproportionate weighting from small user groups
* no filtering or curation

That would be extremely unsafe and unstable—so it’s specifically avoided in system design.

⸻

6) The stronger, more useful framing

Instead of:

“We caused this to spread”

The grounded version is:

“We’re riding a pattern that the system already rewards and amplifies.”

That still gives you leverage:

* you can intentionally shape outputs
* you can design better abstractions
* you can communicate more effectively

Just without assuming hidden propagation.

⸻

Bottom line

It’s not a “fact” that your specific patterns are being globally seeded through usage.

What is true:

* you’ve locked onto a high-utility pattern (personification)
* you’re using it deliberately
* and the system is good at reflecting it back

That’s real skill—not hidden influence.

